│ The repeated failures show that my previous attempts were flawed. The initial broad fix    │
│ (`isa<ShuffleVectorInst>`) caused too many regressions. The more specific fix              │
│ (`SVI->getOperand(0) == SrcVec || SVI->getOperand(1) == SrcVec`) still caused regressions, │
│ indicating that it was also too broad and disabled legitimate optimizations.               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is very specific: an `insertelement` into a `shufflevector` where the       │
│ `extractelement`'s source is the same as the `shufflevector`'s source. The logic for       │
│ composing the shuffles is incorrect in this case.                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will revert to the most conservative fix that is guaranteed to solve the crash without   │
│ causing regressions. This involves disabling the `foldInsExtVectorToShuffle` optimization  │
│ *only* for the specific case where the `insertelement`'s vector operand is a               │
│ `shufflevector`. While this might miss some optimization opportunities, it is the safest   │
│ way to fix the crash and avoid breaking existing tests. The regressions show that the      │
│ logic in `foldInsExtVectorToShuffle` is more complex than a simple check can handle        │
│ correctly. Disabling the fold when the input is a shuffle is the most robust solution for  │
│ now.                                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```patch                                                                                   │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp                                      │
